Wrapping New Zealand's North Island


When we sailed into Mahurangi on Thursday 2nd April we crossed our track from before Christmas, closing the loop on our New Zealand adventures and a circumnavigation of the North Island. Although we had hoped to make it around the South Island too, our priority was to make sure we relax, enjoy ourselves and get back into life out on the water after our year in the marina. In which case we're proud to report that our cruise around (some of) New Zealand was thoroughly successful, despite the weather's best efforts. We spent two months down on the South Island, explored some wonderful cruising grounds, typically stunning New Zealand scenery, and even made it South as far as Christchurch.

We had, naively perhaps despite the stories, anticipated an easier summer cruise than the New Zealand weather offered us. Our overriding experience of the sailing, and a caution to anyone unfamiliar with these waters, is that New Zealand experiences weather. Lots of it!

My memory of the route over these four months is firmly tied to the weather and regular strong winds that we had to plan for and find appropriate shelter from. This was broadly as follows:
 - Christmas in Kawau, sheltering from 30kn 
 - Arrived in the Bay of Islands before New Year, in time to get into Opua marina ahead of forecast 40+kn
 - Almost arrived in Golden Bay on the South Island ahead of a Southerly change, the final 50 miles were upwind in 20-25kn. We then stayed put for a week off Tata Beach waiting for 30kn gusting 50+ around Separation Point to abate, watching spindrift circuling around the anchorage and trying not to drown in the rain - it was wet!
 - After (finally) cruising though the Abel Tasman we headed to Nelson. Whilst anchored in the river outside the marina we had a day of 30kn gusting 40+ perpendicular to the 3kn tide, with 50kn reported in the marina - this is the windiest we've experienced on anchor anywhere.
 - We hid several times during our three weeks in the Marlborough Sounds, standard practice with extremely strong winds the norm in the Cook Straight. On one occassion, deep in Pelorus Sound, 70kn was reported off Wellington and 13m waves. No thanks!
 - We were beaten into Lyttleton by a Southerly, fortunately only by an hour this time. This one was wet and cold and following a surreal mayday event on arrival (a day boat was lost of the rocks in the bay we anchored in) we opted for the marina for a week whilst we jumped ship and stayed with the cousins
 - Great barrier island served up a two day storm, with 50kn reported both North and South. We anchored this one out in good company with lots of other boats, we were lucky in a relatively protected spot compared to others. When it rains here, it rains - something like 150mm rain with this one (>5in).
 - Just to top it off, our first weekend after hauling out on arrival back to Whangarei saw a tropical cyclone pass close by. We took up friends (thanks James and Steph!) on their offer of a bed for this one.

However, all this is only one aspect of the story and totally misses out the main point - cruising New Zealand has been immensely enjoyable, rewarding and yes (well, mostly) relaxing. We have had so many amazing experiences, seen some spectacular coastlines, wildlife and landscapes (as you would expect from New Zealand) and also enjoyed some lovely warm summer weather. We have sailed around some of New Zealand's intimidating corners and headlands - Cape Reinga (top of the North Island), Cape Stephens (top of D'Urville Island, above the Marlborough Sounds), Cape Jackson (corner of the Marborough Sounds, edge of the Cook Straight), and East Cape (Eastern most point of the North Island) - all in benign conditions with the sun shining. However, there's no denying the fact that the water temperature here is not tropical, however much we tried to persuade Sophie!

Sailing back into Whangarei was a surreal experience, we are firmly home from home coming back into the Town Basin. When we leave this time, very soon now, it will be for good and is going to be a tough one for us. Fortunately we are all very excited about getting back to the tropics and experiencing everything that Fiji and Vanuatu have to offer, and who knows what beyond...?!
